<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Energy</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
		<span class="date">Jan. 31, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.fsec.ucf.edu">Florida Solar Energy Center</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Researchers at the
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
University of
<placename></placename>
Central FloridaÂ’s
<place></place>
<placename></placename>
Florida
<placename></placename>
Solar
<placename></placename>
Energy
<placetype></placetype>
Center can speak with reporters about the energy proposals that President Bush is expected to discuss during his State of the Union address on Tuesday, Jan. 31.</p>
<p><strong>Hydrogen experts:</strong></p>
<p><strong>James Fenton</strong>, FSEC director, specializes in hydrogen fuel cells that can be used for vehicles and electronics and as emergency power sources in homes. He researches sustainable energy, electrochemical engineering, environmental engineering and pollution prevention. He is the lead researcher in a recently announced U.S. Department of Energy-funded fuel cell program to conduct research on membranes, which function like spark plugs in vehicles.</p>
<p>For more information: <a href="http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/fenton.htm">http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/fenton.htm</a></p>
<p>Contact: 321-638-1002, <a href="mailto:jfenton@fsec.ucf.edu">jfenton@fsec.ucf.edu </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Ali T-Raissi</strong>, director of the hydrogen division, is a 20-year veteran of hydrogen research and development. He has carried out extensive research in many areas, including hydrogen energy, solar fuels and chemicals and biomass energy conversion.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>For more information: <a href="http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/raissi.htm">http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/raissi.htm </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Contact: 321-638-1446, <a href="mailto:ali@fsec.ucf.edu">ali@fsec.ucf.edu </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Solar power expert:</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Charles Cromer</strong>, interim director of the Photovoltaics Division, is an expert in cells that convert sunlight into electricity. His other specialties include swimming pool heating systems, solar thermal systems and dehumidification and dryer systems.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>For more information: <a href="http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/cromer.htm">http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/cromer.htm </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Contact: 321-638-1455, <a href="mailto:charlie@fsec.ucf.edu">charlie@fsec.ucf.edu </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Energy efficiency expert:</strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Robin Vieira</strong>, director of the Buildings Research division, specializes in green building technologies and standards and is a founder of the Florida Green Building Coalition. He participated in the development of FGBC green guidelines for homes and standards for commercial buildings.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>For more information: <a href="http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/vieira.htm">http://fsec.ucf.edu/about/staff/vieira.htm </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Contact: 321-638-1404, <a href="mailto:robin@fsec.ucf.edu">robin@fsec.ucf.edu </a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The
<place></place>
<placename></placename>
Florida
<placename></placename>
Solar
<placename></placename>
Energy
<placetype></placetype>
Center is the largest and most active state-supported energy research center in the country. Buildings research has helped save <state></state>
<place></place>
Florida residents more than $2.2 billion in energy costs, and FSEC has trained more than 15,000 industry professionals, government officials and others.</p>
<p>For assistance in contacting any of the sources above, reporters can contact Chad Binette, university writer, at 407-823-6312 or <a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">cbinette@mail.ucf.edu </a>, or Tom Evelyn, associate director of News &amp; Information, at 407-823-5988 or <a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
